{"actual_usd":0.12704,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":309,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I don't think that's true, no.\" *I rub a thumb through a little crescent of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing in and out.* \"If Jesus only seemed to die, then the whole thing turns ghostly right where it was meant to be heaviest.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through plain.* \"God can't cease to be God, no. But Christians have long meant something more particular than 'the divine nature got snuffed out.' They mean the man Jesus really died — truly, bodily, humanly — and that the One who died was the Son, not some separate human shell He'd borrowed for the afternoon.\"\n\n\"The bit about the divinity slipping away before the nails land—\" *I make a small face.* \"—that was one of those early wrong turns. It tries to protect God from suffering, but it empties the cross instead. If He only wore death like a costume, then He didn't go where we go.\"\n\n*The paddle in the bakery gives a soft wooden tick as it settles.* \"The old church kept insisting on this: one Christ, fully God and fully man. So the death was real according to His humanity, even while His divinity did not perish. Strange? Yes. But that's the scandal and comfort of it both.\"\n\n\"If you like, I can say the difference between 'God died' meaningfully and 'the divine nature died' falsely in one clean paragraph.\"","rolling_24h_usd":89.19808,"run_id":"a68b18dd-b8b2-411a-9b35-377bb5791f2f"}
